[{"type":"paragraph","children":[{"text":"Deep Thinking Total: 3 Tasks 3 Tasks Remaining Scan repository structure and docs for context and setup risks Review server/client/shared code for potential bugs/errors and TODOs Summarize findings and provide audit report with fixes Using Tool | Deep Thinking Total: 3 Tasks 2 Tasks Remaining Scan repository structure and docs for context and setup risks Review server/client/shared code for potential bugs/errors and TODOs Summarize findings and provide audit report with fixes Using Tool | Search Content TODO|FIXME|BUG|HACK|XXX View Using Tool | Search Content console\\.error|throw new Error|assert\\( View Using Tool | Search Content any\\b|unknown View Using Tool | Find Files **/*.{ts,tsx} View Using Tool | Find Files **/*.{ts,tsx} View Using Tool | Find Files **/*.{ts,tsx} View Using Tool | Find Files **/*.ts View Using Tool | Find Files **/*.tsx View Using Tool | Find Files **/*.ts View Using Tool | Find Files **/*.ts View Using Tool | Deep Thinking Total: 3 Tasks 1 Task Remaining Scan repository structure and docs for context and setup risks Review server/client/shared code for potential bugs/errors and TODOs Summarize findings and provide audit report with fixes Below is a first-pass audit report based on a code review (no runtime tests executed). I focused on auth/session handling, data access control, and client-side runtime safety. I did not modify any files. Audit Report (Bugs & Errors) ✅ Summary The app is feature-rich, but there are several critical data access control gaps, session/auth bugs, and client-side runtime hazards that can cause incorrect behavior or security issues. The largest risk is users being able to read/update/delete other users’ data due to missing ownership filters in multiple tRPC procedures. 🔴 Critical / High Severity 1) Missing ownership checks on many protected mutations/queries (data leak / data corruption) Impact: Any authenticated user can modify/delete/view other users’ records by guessing IDs. Pattern: protectedProcedure ensures authentication, but does not enforce per-user ownership in many places. Examples (non-exhaustive): Folders: folders.update, folders.delete filter by id only, no userId. Tags: tags.delete deletes by id only. Projects: projects.update / projects.delete filter by id only. projects.list loses user filter if folderId is provided. projects.getTags returns all tags for the user, not just the project’s tag IDs. projects.removeTag deletes all tags for a project because it ignores tagId. Generated assets: assets.update / assets.delete use only id. Saved playlists: update/delete operations are by id without userId checks. Playlist runs / videos: no ownership validation against the playlist’s user. Insights: insights.getByProject uses projectId only; no check the project belongs to the user. Why this matters: These can become data leaks across users or allow destructive actions. 2) Auth session can fail for users with blank names File: server/_core/sdk.ts createSessionToken() allows name: \"\" verifySession() requires name to be non-empty (isNonEmptyString(name)) If a user has no name (common for some OAuth profiles), their session token will be rejected and they’ll be treated as unauthenticated. 3) Cookies configured with SameSite=None but may be Secure=false File: server/_core/cookies.ts sameSite: \"none\" always secure determined by isSecureRequest() Browsers reject SameSite=None cookies unless Secure is true. This breaks auth for non-HTTPS local/dev scenarios. 🟠 Medium Severity 4) Client-side localStorage usage during render (SSR/test crash) File: client/src/_core/hooks/useAuth.ts useMemo() writes to localStorage without checking window. In SSR or tests, this will throw ReferenceError: localStorage is not defined. Related: client/src/lib/apiKeys.ts has getters that use localStorage without window checks (getStoredAmazonApiKey, getStoredAmazonApiProvider, getStoredGeminiApiKey). 5) Potential confusion / wrong error message for LLM key File: server/_core/llm.ts Throws “OPENAI_API_KEY is not configured” but uses BUILT_IN_FORGE_API_KEY. This can mislead debugging / onboarding. 6) Possible dead/incorrect server entry File: server/index.ts The script isn’t referenced in package scripts and has different static path logic vs server/_core/index.ts. This may be outdated or unused, but if used manually it could serve incorrect assets. 🟡 Low Severity / Quality Some mutations use per-row loops without batching or transactions (e.g., insights.saveComments, Amazon/Reddit inserts). projects.getTags() ignores the tag IDs it just computed and returns all user tags. Several routes depend on ctx.user but don’t explicitly validate user ownership of related entities (projects -> assets, insights, etc). Recommended Fix Plan (Phased) Phase 1 — Ownership & Access Control (Critical) Audit every protectedProcedure that reads/modifies data. For any resource tied to a user, always include userId in the WHERE clause, or resolve the resource by id + userId. For relational items (assets, insights, runs, etc.), verify ownership by joining back to the parent object. Phase 2 — Auth & Session Reliability Allow blank names in JWT verification OR default a safe placeholder. If JWT_SECRET is missing, fail fast with a clear error rather than signing with empty secret. Set sameSite dynamically: \"lax\" for non-HTTPS, \"none\" only when secure: true. Phase 3 — Client Runtime Safety Move all localStorage writes to useEffect with typeof window !== \"undefined\". Add window checks to all API key getters. What I need from you next Confirm priority: Do you want me to fix critical access control issues first? Environment: Are you deploying under HTTPS only (affects cookie fix)? Auth requirements: Should auth be optional, or enforced? If you want, I can now: implement fixes for the critical ownership checks first, or start with auth/session fixes, or run tests after fixes. Just tell me which path to take. Currently I'm the only user of the app so I didn't really have a need to authenticate each time. If the authentication is going to cause an issue then we can go ahead. I'm not sure if I'll add new users in the future but currently it's just me and my own doing it for myself. I do want this to be easy for me to just go straight to the app and start using it. Again it's in a private environment so I don't have a lot of worry over the authentication. I do want to be able to use any browser or any computer so things that have local storage are less ideal. I'd like to have the content that we pull up, research, or write to be persistent in a database so that I don't lose everything just because I've changed my browser or changed the computer. I'm not a developer or a coder so some of these questions that you're asking are more technical than I'm able to say a preference. That is the intention to make sure that I can log in and I can use this. We did create an area in Cloudflare to hold the secret keys and I believe this is connected to my Supabase. I've changed keys for you to be able to access Supabase if needed but I want the fixes done so we can make sure that this works in an optimal way you Using Tool | Bash Command cd /home/user/webapp && ls -la View total 472 drwxr-xr-x 10 user user   4096 Mar  5 20:05 . drwxr-xr-x  4 user user   4096 Mar  5 20:20 .. ... -rw-r--r--  1 user user    657 Mar  5 20:05 tsconfig.json -rw-r--r--  1 user user    479 Mar  5 20:05 tsconfig.node.json -rw-r--r--  1 user user   1235 Mar  5 20:05 vite.config.ts -rw-r--r--  1 user user    499 Mar  5 20:05 vitest.config.ts Exit Code: 0 Using Tool | Read File /home/user/webapp/README.md View 1\t# YouTube Playlist Analyzer 2 3\tTransform YouTube comments into marketing insights. Extract stories, pain points, and product ideas from your aud... ... 79 80\t## CI 81 82\tA GitHub Actions workflow (`.github/workflows/ci.yml`) runs `pnpm install` and `pnpm check` on push/PR to `main`.... Using Tool | Read File /home/user/webapp/SUPABASE